# Essential Red Hat Linux Commands (A–Z)

Below is a clean, simple list of **150+ essential Linux commands**, numbered step‑by‑step (1, 2, 3...) for easy learning.

---

## A — Commands
1. `alias` – Create shortcut for commands  
2. `awk` – Text processing tool  
3. `apt` – Package manager (Debian-based, not RHEL but commonly referenced)  
4. `at` – Schedule a one-time task  
5. `apropos` – Search commands by description  

## B — Commands
6. `bash` – GNU Bourne-Again shell  
7. `basename` – Strip directory from filename  
8. `bc` – Calculator  
9. `bg` – Resume job in background  
10. `blkid` – Identify block devices  
11. `blockdev` – Manage block device params  
12. `bootctl` – Boot manager control  
13. `break` – Stop loop execution  

## C — Commands
14. `cal` – Display calendar  
15. `cat` – Show contents of file  
16. `cd` – Change directory  
17. `chgrp` – Change group of a file  
18. `chmod` – Change permissions  
19. `chown` – Change owner  
20. `chroot` – Change root directory  
21. `cksum` – Checksum  
22. `clear` – Clear terminal  
23. `cmp` – Compare files  
24. `comm` – Compare sorted files  
25. `cp` – Copy file/directory  
26. `crontab` – Cron job scheduler  
27. `curl` – Transfer data from URL  
28. `cut` – Cut columns from file  

## D — Commands
29. `date` – Show/Set system date  
30. `df` – Disk usage (filesystem level)  
31. `diff` – Show differences between files  
32. `dig` – DNS lookup tool  
33. `dmesg` – Kernel message buffer  
34. `dnf` – RHEL package manager  
35. `du` – Disk usage (directory/file)  

## E — Commands
36. `echo` – Print text  
37. `egrep` – Extended grep  
38. `env` – Environment variables  
39. `exit` – Exit shell  
40. `export` – Export environment variable  

## F — Commands
41. `fdisk` – Partitioning tool  
42. `fg` – Bring job to foreground  
43. `find` – Search files  
44. `firewall-cmd` – Firewalld tool  
45. `free` – Memory usage  
46. `fsck` – File system check  

## G — Commands
47. `groupadd` – Create group  
48. `groupdel` – Delete group  
49. `groupmod` – Modify group  
50. `grep` – Pattern search  
51. `gunzip` – Unzip gzip file  

## H — Commands
52. `halt` – Stop machine  
53. `head` – Show first lines  
54. `history` – Show command history  
55. `hostname` – Show hostname  

## I — Commands
56. `iconv` – Convert text encoding  
57. `id` – Print user identity  
58. `ifconfig` – Network interface (older tool)  
59. `ip` – Modern network config tool  
60. `iotop` – Monitor disk I/O  
61. `iptables` – Network firewall  

## J — Commands
62. `jobs` – Show job list  
63. `journalctl` – View systemd logs  

## K — Commands
64. `kill` – Stop processes  
65. `killall` – Kill processes by name  
66. `kmod` – Kernel module manager  

## L — Commands
67. `last` – Login history  
68. `less` – View file page by page  
69. `ln` – Create links  
70. `locate` – Fast file lookup  
71. `login` – Start session  
72. `ls` – List files  
73. `lscpu` – Show CPU info  
74. `lsblk` – Block device info  
75. `lsmod` – Kernel module list  

## M — Commands
76. `make` – Build automation  
77. `man` – Manual pages  
78. `mkdir` – Create directory  
79. `more` – View file page by page  
80. `mount` – Mount device  
81. `mv` – Move/rename files  

## N — Commands
82. `nano` – Editor  
83. `nc` – Netcat networking tool  
84. `netstat` – Network connections  
85. `nmcli` – NetworkManager tool  
86. `nslookup` – DNS lookup  

## O — Commands
87. `openssl` – SSL/TLS tool  
88. `passwd` – Change password  
89. `ping` – Test connectivity  

## P — Commands
90. `pkill` – Kill by name  
91. `ps` – Process status  
92. `pwd` – Print working directory  

## Q — Commands
93. `quota` – Disk quota  

## R — Commands
94. `reboot` – Restart machine  
95. `rm` – Delete files  
96. `rmdir` – Delete empty directory  
97. `rsync` – File sync tool  

## S — Commands
98. `scp` – Secure copy  
99. `screen` – Terminal multiplexer  
100. `sed` – Stream editor  
101. `semanage` – SELinux management  
102. `service` – Start/stop services  
103. `shutdown` – Shutdown machine  
104. `sleep` – Delay execution  
105. `sort` – Sort text file  
106. `ss` – Socket statistics  
107. `stat` – File info  
108. `sudo` – Run as superuser  
109. `systemctl` – systemd manager  

## T — Commands
110. `tail` – Last lines of file  
111. `tar` – Archive tool  
112. `tee` – Output to file & screen  
113. `top` – CPU/Process monitor  
114. `touch` – Create empty file  
115. `tr` – Translate characters  
116. `tree` – Directory tree  
117. `tty` – Terminal name  

## U — Commands
118. `ufw` – Firewall tool (not default RHEL)  
119. `umount` – Unmount device  
120. `uname` – System info  
121. `unzip` – Extract zip files  
122. `useradd` – Add user  
123. `userdel` – Delete user  
124. `usermod` – Modify user  

## V — Commands
125. `vdir` – Verbose directory listing  
126. `vi` – Editor  
127. `vim` – Improved editor  
128. `vmstat` – System performance  

## W — Commands
129. `w` – Show logged in users  
130. `wall` – Broadcast message  
131. `wc` – Word count  
132. `wget` – Download files  
133. `whereis` – Locate command  
134. `which` – Show command path  
135. `who` – Logged in users  
136. `whoami` – Show current user  

## X — Commands
137. `xdg-open` – Open files (desktop systems)  

## Y — Commands
138. `yum` – Older RHEL package manager  

## Z — Commands
139. `zip` – Create zip  
140. `zcat` – View compressed file  
141. `zgrep` – Grep inside .gz file  
142. `zless` – View gz file  
143. `zsh` – Shell  

---

